### Description

Hi I'm trying to implement a feature flag system based on versioned components where the feature flags are served by a FeatureFlagService that know what component should be declare. Also it should be agnostic for the developer developing with the versioned components. And for this case I need to declare components in modules dynamically based on dependencies.

### Proposed solution

I've been thinking on a solution where the declarations passed to module could be similar to providers that have deps array and useFactory function to resolve the Component.
Would look something like this.
```
@NgModule({
  imports: [...],
  declarations: [AppComponent, {
    useFactory: (flagService: FeatureFlagService) => {
      // do whatever with deps and return a component
    },
    deps: [FeatureFlagService]
  }],
  bootstrap: [AppComponent],
})
export class AppModule {}
```

### Alternatives considered

I've considered several alternatives like structural directives or simply directive but the problem is that it will make the development of the code non agnostic for the FeatureFlagService, giving code like:
`
<versioned-component [options]="{
   v1: Component1,
   v2: Component2,
   ....
  }"
</versioned-component>
`

I've struggled to find how to filter tests `ng test` for one specific case: running slow tests separately but still with Karma / Jasmine.
Two pre-existing (but closed) issues (#3603 and #3436) partially addressed the problem but I think I managed to find a more elegant solution than @danday74 and @EugeneSnihovsky suggestions, though they address another problem: filtering by file name.

`ng test --include` did not work for me as it only includes the files that are given to it; meaning that if your test file depends on a production file, both have to be mentioned. This is not useful at all.

In the end my solution is quite simple (works for karma + jasmine) and filters by test name only:

```javascript
// some-test.spec.js

it("#slow run a full check", () => {...});

it("run a rapid check", () => {...});
```

```javascript
// karma.conf.js

// Use an environment variable to pass the search regex
const KARMA_GREP = process.env.KARMA_GREP;

// Add client.args in config
module.exports = function (config) {
  config.set({
    // Use the karma-jasmine client configuration
    client: {
      ...(KARMA_GREP && {
        args: ["--grep", KARMA_GREP],
      }),
    },
}
```

And run in the CLI

```bash
# Run #slow tests
KARMA_GREP='#slow' ng test
# Run not #slow tests
KARMA_GREP='/^(?!.*#slow).*$/' ng test
```

Since `KARMA_GREP` can be a regular expression, it is quite versatile

